{
  "text": "Viability of RRV-infected Caco-2 cells and evaluation of the percentage of cells infected. We used human cDNA microarrays to study the global transcriptional response of cells infected with rotavirus. We chose the human intestinal cell line Caco-2 (16) as a model that would mimic characteristics of rotavirus replication in vivo. Caco-2 cells were derived from a human colon adenocarcinoma and display several characteristics of mature enterocytes, such as cellular polarization, development of an apical brush border membrane, and expression of intestinal hydrolases on the apical domain [CITATION_1] . In addition, Caco-2 cells have been used to study the interaction of several enteropathogens with the intestine [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , and most rotavirus strains, including our laboratory strain RRV, grow efficiently in Caco-2 cells [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
